So the story is a little slow with silver linings occasionally but to me that's not a bad thing. I find alot of profound meaning in moments like that, as our collie says about the beach with her siblings. To me I've spent a lot of time snorkeling/scuba in cold water and when your in the water or waiting in the back of a boat, alot of the time the world feels surreal and it's own particular version of calm that settles over it. Tends to make us thoughtful in ways we otherwise are not. I imagine it's similar to what it might be like to live on an airship. To me it feels like an extension of how it might sink into a mind or a narrative. It's not super typical to find that feeling in writing, especially writeing thats not full of philosophical navel gazing.

As for story stuff moving forwards, polish off some more important character interactions and lean harder into the mystery around them. I may be misinterpreting some of this as I am not a great writer myself but as far as goalpost go I think you have been ticking through them at a good pace. We got some good world building, some very intriguing plot hooks, and both were used to push the likable characters into growing individually as well as growing into each other. They fought to survive and for each other to survive too.

As for Degeneracy Pressure
The 3-4 transition is fine. I often think first contact goes a little too well or far too poorly, and this does a good job of straddling that line, bouncing between awkward, and terrifying. (Also every reader knows for meta reasons that he is not going to die, and that there will be a space wife) Ultimately I think more of story is going to be about her and her situation/the situation she caused.
